Been rereading early William Gibson books. They hold up surprisingly well. Now on Mona Lisa Overdrive, which is such a great title.

I think the reason William Gibson’s Sprawl trilogy feels vibrant and alive, even after 30+ years, is that even that it seems like it’s about future technology, it’s really about people’s feelings and relationship to that tech and each other.
A recurring theme in Gibson’s Sprawl trilogy novels is how massive concentrations of wealth distort, corrupt, and contort the world and people within it. Feels pretty relevant these days!

There’s a deep sadness in Mona Lisa Overdrive, a nostalgic yearning for the broken and fallen worlds of Neuromancer and Count Zero. There’s a feeling that world has drifted into an ennui that it can’t recover from.
I’ve always felt that social media companies have been extremely presumptuous with how they throw around the word “friend”.

“friend”? a close, personal relationship. “acquaintance” comes closer to the watered-down version that social media companies mean. Better to come up with a new word, I think. “droog” isn’t bad if you want to lean into the sinister nature of all this junk :D
but I’m more of a descriptivist when it comes to language. I dig the organic way language evolves. “friend” in a social media sense is a sterile, corporate imposition on all of us

Before that, posting to internet was a sitting at computer activity before then
A message for each post. Also, I had to pay for each SMS! It was 10 cents each time. So I only wrote something when I had an idea I really liked.

Some people were probably smarter and had an SMS plan that didn’t cost them every time.
